07:37.223 --> 07:41.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL SCHMIDT, The New York
Times: Well,
we wrote our story
two-and-a-half weeks ago,

07:41.194 --> 07:46.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where we said that Mr. O'Reilly
had settled
harassment cases with five
women, including

07:46.499 --> 07:49.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two in the past year, since
Roger Ailes had
left the network.

07:49.402 --> 07:55.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at the time of our story,
the Murdoch
family was really standing by
Mr. O'Reilly.

07:55.475 --> 07:58.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They looked like they wanted to
keep him on.

07:58.478 --> 08:00.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what happened was that he
began to lose
advertisers.

08:00.847 --> 08:05.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First, he lost Mercedes-Benz,
the first one
to go, and then dozens and
dozens of companies,

08:05.918 --> 08:07.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
went up to about 50.

08:07.787 --> 08:13.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what you had was an 8:00
hour, the prime
time on the network, that had
just a few ads

08:13.359 --> 08:15.194 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
running on it.

08:15.228 --> 08:18.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at the same time, FOX had
brought in an
outside law firm to do an
investigation into

08:18.764 --> 08:24.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
