to be made for not giving it to
the church.

27:32.884 --> 27:34.853 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's right.

27:34.886 --> 27:40.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The church's lawyer said that
there is actually
coercion here, that the church
is being penalized

27:40.125 --> 27:44.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because of its status as a
religious organization.

27:44.162 --> 27:50.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We also heard on the other side
Justices Alito
and Breyer, for example, gave a
whole series

27:51.002 --> 27:58.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of hypotheticals to the state's
attorney,
saying, can the constitution
require a state

27:59.010 --> 28:04.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to deny police services or fire
services to
religious institutions?

28:04.983 --> 28:06.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the state's lawyer said,
well, no.

28:06.951 --> 28:11.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Justice Breyer said, well,
what's the
difference here with the
playground where

28:11.523 --> 28:14.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're trying to keep little
children from
falling and breaking their
ankles?

28:14.959 --> 28:20.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Even some of the
more liberal
justices were arguing -- or
seemed to be argue

28:20.665 --> 28:22.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in favor of the church.

28:22.133 --> 28:24.002 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: In favor, yes,
exactly.

28:24.035 --> 28:29.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the state's argument comes
back to this:
Look, we don't want to get
entangled with

28:29.674 --> 28:30.642 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
churches.

28:30.675 --> 28:32.077 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a neutral program.

28:32.110 --> 28:34.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We don't want to be selecting
among churches.

28:34.879 --> 28:41.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we don't want to be sending
a check directly
to a church for a physical
improvement.

28:41.119 --> 28:44.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now, the reason
people watch
these things is not only because
of a playground,

28:45.023 --> 28:45.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but larger implications.

28:46.024 --> 28:47.959 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Absolutely.

28:47.992 --> 28:51.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In this case
particularly because
there are bigger societal
questions for about,

28:51.429 --> 28:53.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for example, school voucher
programs.

28:53.064 --> 28:54.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes.

28:54.899 --> 28:58.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, a lot of the religious
organizations
that are supporting the church
in this case

28:58.303 --> 29:05.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really believe that this could
say a lot about
states that do now have
obstacles to school

29:05.443 --> 29:07.178 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
vouchers.

29:07.212 --> 29:12.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it also may have an impact
on a whole
range of state-funded programs
that do not

29:12.450 --> 29:14.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accept applications or support
religious organizations.

29:14.919 --> 29:16.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

29:16.621 --> 29:19.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In our last minute, the first
week of Justice
Neil Gorsuch, you got to watch
him.

29:20.024 --> 29:21.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I happened to be there myself on
Monday.

29:21.493 --> 29:22.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: I know you were.

29:22.494 --> 29:23.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What did you see?

29:23.495 --> 29:25.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, he's very
well-prepared.

29:25.296 --> 29:31.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was very active on a hot
bench, although
I think by late today he was
getting a little

29:31.903 --> 29:33.138 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tired.

29:33.171 --> 29:36.407 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He wasn't asking as many
questions as he did
that first day.

29:36.441 --> 29:40.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He injects a certain amount of
humor, and
he seems to have a testy side to
him.

29:40.712 --> 29:41.679 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A little bite.

29:41.713 --> 29:42.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Every now and
then, yes.

29:42.881 --> 29:44.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

29:44.115 --> 29:45.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When he wants to, he can go back
and forth
quite sharply.

29:46.017 --> 29:46.985 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes, he can.

29:47.018 --> 29:48.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

29:48.787 --> 29:52.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All right, we will be watching
the future
of Justice Neil Gorsuch and all
things with

29:52.157 --> 29:53.124 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

29:53.158 --> 29:55.860 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Marcia Coyle, thanks as always.

29:55.894 --> 30:01.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Thank you, Jeff.

30:01.699 --> 30:09.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thousands of
Venezuelans took
to the streets in protest again
today.

30:09.340 --> 30:14.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two demonstrators were killed,
as a political
crisis in this failing state
deepens.

30:14.979 --> 30:18.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our chief foreign affairs
correspondent, Margaret
Warner, reports.

30:18.817 --> 30:22.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Organizers
dubbed it the
Mother of All Marches.

30:22.720 --> 30:28.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Hundreds of thousands of
opponents to socialist
President Nicolas Maduro flooded
Caracas.

30:28.059 --> 30:32.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD BLANCO, Venezuela
(through translator):
Today, people are in the street
demonstrating

30:33.031 --> 30:37.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
peacefully, seeking a democratic
exit to a
situation that is already
overflowing.

30:37.502 --> 30:40.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here, the president of the
republic is playing
with fire.

30:40.471 --> 30:45.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The peace was
broken almost
immediately, as protesters
clashed with police

30:45.410 --> 30:47.979 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and government supporters.

30:48.012 --> 30:52.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Guard troops fired tear
gas, and
a teenage boy died after being
shot in the

30:52.917 --> 30:54.652 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
head.

30:54.686 --> 30:59.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Demonstrators have tried
repeatedly in recent
days to reach the capital city's
downtown.

30:59.858 --> 31:02.560 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Each time, they were turned back
by riot police.

31:02.594 --> 31:07.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At least five people were
killed, and hundreds
arrested.

31:07.799 --> 31:12.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Brian Ellsworth of Reuters,
speaking to us
by Skype from Caracas, said
tensions have

31:12.937 --> 31:14.839 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
been building.

31:14.873 --> 31:17.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRIAN ELLSWORTH, Reuters: This
has been sort
of the culmination of that,
about two-and-a-half

31:17.742 --> 31:20.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
weeks of all these
demonstrations.

31:20.078 --> 31:24.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The opposition called this big
demonstration
and said, all over the country,
we need to

31:24.249 --> 31:26.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be protesting against the
government.

31:26.117 --> 31:32.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: These latest
protests erupted
last month, after the
pro-government Supreme

31:32.090 --> 31:37.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Court took over the powers of
the national
legislature controlled by the
opposition.

31:37.528 --> 31:40.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After an international outcry,
the court reversed
itself.

31:41.032 --> 31:42.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But the criticism continued.

31:42.400 --> 31:46.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
haven't done
anything.

31:46.237 --> 31:49.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Supreme Court has installed
a coup d'etat
it cannot correct.

31:49.107 --> 31:55.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The oil-rich
nation is also
mired in an economic crisis,
with skyrocketing,

31:55.079 --> 31:59.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
triple-digit inflation, rampant
crime and
food shortages.

31:59.817 --> 32:05.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The opposition wants Maduro's
removed, new
elections and the release of
political prisoners,

32:05.957 --> 32:11.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including opposition leader
Leopoldo Lopez,
who was jailed in early 2014.

32:11.529 --> 32:17.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In February, Lopez's wife went
to the White
House with Florida Senator Marco
Rubio.

32:17.268 --> 32:22.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump tweeted a photo
with her,
saying: "Venezuela should allow
Leopoldo Lopez,

32:22.473 --> 32:26.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a political prisoner, out of
prison immediately."

32:26.244 --> 32:31.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That same month, the U.S.
Treasury Department
designated Venezuelan Vice
President Tareck

32:31.449 --> 32:36.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
El Aissami for sanctions on drug
trafficking
charges.

32:36.387 --> 32:38.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Secretary of State Rex Tillerson
today:

32:38.423 --> 32:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON, U.S. Secretary of
State: We
are concerned that the
government of Maduro

32:41.626 --> 32:47.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is violating its own
Constitution and is not
allowing the opposition to have
their voices

32:47.098 --> 32:48.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
heard.

32:48.599 --> 32:50.935 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Maduro has
blamed the U.S.
for trying to foment a coup.

32:50.969 --> 32:55.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICOLAS MADURO, Venezuelan
President (through
translator): The time for combat
has arrived,

32:55.139 --> 32:56.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
my fellow patriots.

32:56.641 --> 32:59.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The hour has arrived to decide
the future
and the destiny of our country.

32:59.978 --> 33:04.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Maduro came to
power four
years ago, upon the death of his
charismatic

33:04.182 --> 33:06.517 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
predecessor, Hugo Chavez.

33:06.551 --> 33:09.320 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Maduro has struggled ever since.

33:09.354 --> 33:15.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chavez himself survived a brief
coup in 2002,
and accused the United States of
trying to

33:15.593 --> 33:17.395 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
subvert him.

33:17.428 --> 33:23.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Riding on high world oil prices,
Chavez had
created subsidies and price
controls, raising

33:23.201 --> 33:26.904 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
living standards for the poor,
but no longer.

33:26.938 --> 33:28.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Again, Brian Ellsworth:

33:28.706 --> 33:32.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRIAN ELLSWORTH: Once oil prices
collapsed
in 2014, the country basically
hadn't saved

33:32.744 --> 33:34.479 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
money during the oil boom.

33:34.512 --> 33:37.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Private enterprise has a really
hard time
producing goods and services,
which means

33:37.415 --> 33:39.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we basically don't have them.

33:39.350 --> 33:43.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: The Maduro
regime is also
under pressure from its Latin
American neighbors.

33:43.988 --> 33:48.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Eleven countries called this
week for a time
frame to hold elections.

33:48.126 --> 33:52.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

33:52.964 --> 34:03.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: Is the
scientific community
finding its political voice?

34:03.975 --> 34:08.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Science correspondent Miles
O'Brien looks
into what is behind street
protests here staged

34:08.746 --> 34:12.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by members of a profession not
generally known
for their activism.

34:12.717 --> 34:15.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of our weekly Leading
Edge series.

34:15.753 --> 34:20.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Who is ready to stand up
for science?

34:20.658 --> 34:22.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

34:22.393 --> 34:27.899 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: They are
scientists, and on
this February Sunday in Boston,
they were

34:27.932 --> 34:31.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conducting an experiment they'd
just as soon
avoid.

34:31.936 --> 34:37.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Facing a White House that is
pushing across-the-board
steep cuts in federal science
funding, they

34:37.075 --> 34:38.743 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are taking to the streets.

34:38.776 --> 34:40.445 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Their hypothesis?

34:40.478 --> 34:44.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In order to keep their work
alive, they must
dive into the political fray.

34:44.649 --> 34:48.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY SUPRAN, Massachusetts
Institute of
Technology: Today, science
fights back.

34:48.086 --> 34:49.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

34:49.854 --> 34:54.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY SUPRAN: I think,
scientists, it's
not in our natural nature to
shout, to make

34:54.292 --> 34:57.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a loud noise, but, apparently,
we can do it
when come together.

34:57.728 --> 35:02.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Geoffrey Supran
is a renewable
energy modeler at MIT.

35:02.600 --> 35:07.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was there among a few hundred
protesters
in Copley Square, one of several
protests

35:07.472 --> 35:11.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
staged by scientists since
Donald Trump became
president.

35:11.509 --> 35:16.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The administration has proposed
double-digit
cuts for the Environmental
Protection Agency

35:16.214 --> 35:21.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the National Institutes of
Health, and
a 20 percent across-the-board
cut to research

35:21.919 --> 35:23.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on climate change.

35:23.788 --> 35:29.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEOFFREY SUPRAN: As scientists,
it's actually
our responsibility, and as
citizens, to warn

35:29.427 --> 35:30.728 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the public when we see danger.

35:30.761 --> 35:33.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, if you see something,
say something.

35:33.364 --> 35:35.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we feel the civic duty.

35:35.199 --> 35:39.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The protesters
here hope this
rally is merely a prelude to
something much

35:39.604 --> 35:45.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bigger, a march en masse in
Washington and
hundreds of other cities all
over the world

35:45.176 --> 35:48.146 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on April 22.

35:48.179 --> 35:51.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kishore Hari is one of the
organizers of the
Earth Day events.

35:51.616 --> 35:55.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KISHORE HARI, Protest Organizer:
Science has
been political since the time of
Galileo.

35:55.453 --> 35:57.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nothing has changed between now
and then.

35:57.388 --> 36:01.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's important that we are
nonpartisan
because this is a march for
science, and that

36:01.626 --> 36:03.528 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
unifies everyone around the
world.

36:03.561 --> 36:08.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But the idea has
drawn controversy
from some scientists, who are
concerned march

36:09.000 --> 36:14.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
organizers are also advocating a
host of other
liberal social causes.

36:14.939 --> 36:19.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The rally in Boston happened in
the midst
of the annual meeting of the
largest scientific

36:19.343 --> 36:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
society in the world, the
American Association
for the Advancement of Science.

36:25.183 --> 36:30.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The organization is supporting
the political
mobilization of many of its
members.

36:30.688 --> 36:34.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Physicist and former Democratic
Congressman
Rush Holt is the CEO.

36:34.358 --> 36:39.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RUSH HOLT (D), Former U.S.
Congressman: This
would be -- it's purported to be
a demonstration

36:39.864 --> 36:44.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for science, the very idea of
science, the
essence of science.

36:44.902 --> 36:47.371 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Isn't that a wonderful idea?

36:47.405 --> 36:50.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NAOMI ORESKES, Harvard
University: This rally
isn't about promoting a
particular policy.

36:50.741 --> 36:56.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's about promoting the idea
that the scientific
enterprise as a whole improves
our lives.

36:56.147 --> 37:01.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Naomi Oreskes is
a scientist
and a professor of the history
of science

37:01.285 --> 37:03.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at Harvard University.

37:03.321 --> 37:09.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She has written extensively
about the role
of politics, special interests
and science.

37:09.160 --> 37:14.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For most of history, she says,
scientists
had to be politically and
publicly engaged

37:14.999 --> 37:17.101 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in order to fund their research.

37:17.134 --> 37:23.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in the U.S., that changed
after World
